# Flask DevOps Project – AWS Infrastructure with Terraform

## Overview

This project provisions the AWS infrastructure required to deploy a Dockerized Flask application on Amazon EKS using Terraform.

The infrastructure includes:

* Amazon S3 bucket for Terraform remote state
* Amazon VPC
* Public subnet
* Private subnet
* Amazon EKS cluster
* Two EKS managed node groups
* Amazon ECR repository
* Required IAM roles and permissions

---

## Prerequisites

Before deploying, ensure you have the following installed:

* Terraform (v1.5 or later)
* AWS CLI
* kubectl
* Docker
* AWS account
* Configured AWS credentials

Verify the installations:

```bash
terraform -version
aws --version
kubectl version --client
docker --version
```

---

## Configure AWS Credentials

Configure the AWS CLI:

```bash
aws configure
```

Enter:

* AWS Access Key ID
* AWS Secret Access Key
* Default Region: `us-east-1`
* Output Format: `json`

Verify the credentials:

```bash
aws sts get-caller-identity
```

---

## Clone the Repository

```bash
git clone <repository-url>
cd <repository-folder>
```

---

## Initialize Terraform

Initialize Terraform and download the required providers and modules:

```bash
terraform init
```

If migrating an existing local state to the S3 backend:

```bash
terraform init -migrate-state
```

---

## Review the Execution Plan

Generate the Terraform execution plan:

```bash
terraform plan
```

Review the resources that Terraform will create.

---

## Deploy the Infrastructure

Create all AWS resources:

```bash
terraform apply
```

Type:

```text
yes
```

when prompted.

Terraform will provision:

* S3 backend
* VPC
* Public subnet
* Private subnet
* EKS cluster
* Two managed node groups
* Amazon ECR repository
* IAM roles

---

## Verify the Outputs

Display all Terraform outputs:

```bash
terraform output
```

Example outputs include:

* Cluster name
* Cluster endpoint
* ECR repository URL
* IAM Role ARN
* VPC ID
* Public subnet ID
* Private subnet ID

---

## Configure kubectl

Update the local kubeconfig file:

```bash
aws eks update-kubeconfig \
  --region us-east-1 \
  --name flask-eks
```

Verify the connection:

```bash
kubectl get nodes
```

The worker nodes should appear with a `Ready` status.

---

## Destroy the Infrastructure

To remove all created AWS resources:

```bash
terraform destroy
```

Confirm with:

```text
yes
```

---

